&gt; BigCache does not handle collisions. When new item is inserted and it&#x27;s hash collides with previously stored item, new item overwrites previously stored value.<p>I&#x27;m not sure what hashing algorithm it is using, but this seems like a pretty undesirable property.<p>The code for the hash function is found here: <a href="https:&#x2F;&#x2F;github.com&#x2F;allegro&#x2F;bigcache&#x2F;blob&#x2F;f64abe8f4fe2f5769bd9bef5a2944a83ea673e7e&#x2F;fnv.go#L19-L28" rel="nofollow">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;github.com&#x2F;allegro&#x2F;bigcache&#x2F;blob&#x2F;f64abe8f4fe2f5769bd...</a><p><pre><code>    &#x2F;&#x2F; Sum64 gets the string and returns its uint64 hash value.
    func (f fnv64a) Sum64(key string) uint64 {
        var hash uint64 = offset64
        for i := 0; i &lt; len(key); i++ {
            hash ^= uint64(key[i])
            hash *= prime64
        }
        return hash
    }
</code></pre>
The referenced `offset64` is `14695981039346656037` and the `prime64` is `1099511628211`.<p>I can find a reference to a similarly named `Sum64` function in <a href="https:&#x2F;&#x2F;godoc.org&#x2F;blainsmith.com&#x2F;go&#x2F;seahash#Sum64" rel="nofollow">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;godoc.org&#x2F;blainsmith.com&#x2F;go&#x2F;seahash#Sum64</a> which indicates SeaHash is a non-cryptographic hash function and further considers `Sum64` to be a checksum function.<p>I&#x27;m guessing there&#x27;s a lot more collisions possible here than otherwise expected.
